AWS EC2 

Amazon compute - the power behind running your app = AWS has multiple options 

Amazon compute: 

- EC2 - similar to classic VM’s where you have full control of the OS and how it’s configured = flexible 
- Containers - ECS =  one is a container runner - lightweight version of app that has dependancies packaged sharing host kernel and OS 
- Containers - EKS = container orchestrator with Kubernetes 
- Serverless - Lambda = service that runs your code when triggered by the functions in your code ( AWS handles the server side ) ( can scale up & down based on use )
- High availability and scalability 


EC2 = Elastic compute cloud = infrastructure as a service ( IAAS ) 

- Virtual machines/ servers that you rent from AWS on a by usage basis - ( everything a physical server can do )
- These virtual servers can be SPUN UP to run your app , host websites , process data ect
- Are flexible and can be configured 
- They can be scaled HORIZONTALLY by adding more instances 

* EC2 an be integrated with Load balancers , auto scaling and most AWS services 

EC2 can allow you to : 
- ELASTIC BLOCK STORAGE (EBS) -      storing data on persistent block storage for your EC2 instance 
- ELASTIC LOAD BALANCER (ELB) -   Distributes incoming traffic across multiple EC2 instances 
- AUTO SCALING GROUP (ASG) -    Auto adjusts the number of EC2 instances based on demand = app resilient & cost effective 

Configured with : 

Operating system - ( OS ) 
How much compute power cores - ( CPU)
How much random access memory - ( RAM ) 

How much storage - Network attached = EBS ( like a hard drive attached ) , EFS (share access and data between instances) (mounted)
Network card - speed of card & access to public ip address 
Firewall rules - security group = more resilient and robust against attacks 
Bootstrap script - script written that runs when configured for first EC2 instance launch / spin up 


EC2 user data 

Possible to bootstrap out instances with a EC2 user data script on first launch 
*bootstrap = launching commands when machine first starts *
Script is only run once at first start / launch 

EC2 user data script can automate :      * source code + dependancies + instructions etc = package *
- Installing updates 
- Installing 
- Downloading common files off the internet 

Ec2 user data script runs with the root user so has access to everything 
+ good for setting up multiple instances + reproducibility  


EC2 instance types 

They come in “instance families” that are represented by a letter = m (instance type)  5 . 2xlarge (size within instance class )

T & M = general purpose 
C = focus on compute ( cpu heavy tasks ) 
R = focus on memory  (memory intensive workloads )
I = storage 
G & P = ( GPU acceleration / machine learning ) 
X & U = highly specialised high memory needs 


EC2 purchasing options   - use instance type finder

On demand resource →  short workload and predictable pricing 

Reserved instances 1 & 3 years → long workloads
 
Convertible reserved instances →long workloads with flexible instances 

Savings Plans (1–3 years)
→ Commitment to usage → Flexible instances → long workloads 

Spot instances → short workloads , cheap but can lose instances = LESS RELIABLE - AWS can terminate anytime

Dedicated Hosts → book an entire physical server 

Dedicated Instances
→ Hardware not shared with other customers → Still managed by AWS

Capacity reservations → reserve capacity in a specific AZ ( availability zone ) = Guarantees availability + pay regardless of use 

Dedicated Hosts
→ Entire physical server → Full control (licensing / compliance use cases)

